<div class="card">

    <h2>Automatic Email Classification System (Spam vs Not Spam)</h2>

    <p><strong>Problem:</strong> Users and organizations receive a large number of emails every day, including unwanted spam messages such as advertisements, phishing attempts, or malicious content. Manually filtering these emails is inefficient, time-consuming, and prone to human error. The challenge is to automatically identify and separate spam emails from legitimate ones in a fast and reliable way.</p>

    <p><strong>Type:</strong> This use case relies on supervised learning, specifically classification algorithms. The model is trained using labeled email data (spam and not spam) to learn patterns and distinguish between both categories.</p>

    <p><strong>Input:</strong> The input consists of email data, mainly:
    - The text content of the email
    - Preprocessed textual features (such as word frequency or vectorized text)
    - Labeled examples indicating whether the email is spam or not spam</p>

    <p><strong>Output:</strong> The system outputs:
    - A classification label: Spam or Not Spam
    - (Optional) A probability score indicating the confidence of the prediction</p>

    <p><strong>Relevance:</strong> Email classification systems are widely used in real-world applications such as email services (e.g., Gmail or Outlook) to automatically filter spam, improve user productivity, and protect against phishing or malicious attacks. This helps users focus on important messages while enhancing security and efficiency.</p>

